headline: Cliffs Inks Multiyear Steel Pacts with US Automakers in Tariff Aftershock
summary: While it’s unclear what prices were agreed to, the duration of the agreements mark a notable change for Cliffs, the biggest supplier of automotive steel in the US, whose previous automotive contracts were usually signed in one-year increments.  It indicates some automakers are solidifying multiyear prices of key steel input for their cars and trucks amid widespread concern that President Donald Trump’s tariffs will stoke inflation.  It also shows that Cliffs, which has lost auto market share in recent years, is trying to capitalize on Trump’s steel sector duties.
